summary:
U.S. military forces intercepted Iranian attacks on three Navy ships in the Strait of Hormuz and struck Iranian targets on Thursday amid a declared truce. The Strait handles 20% of global oil transit, and the incidents have affected oil prices. President Trump states the ceasefire holds but threatens escalation without a peace deal. Broader Middle East conflict risks remain.

North Korea announced deployment of new long-range artillery systems capable of striking Seoul this year and its first destroyer soon. The artillery targets the South Korean capital region, home to 25 million people, amid stalled inter-Korean talks. In central Mali, JNIM militants linked to al-Qaeda killed more than 30 people in two attacks on Thursday, per local sources; civilians and security forces were affected. Toyota cut its fiscal year ending March 2027 operating income forecast to ¥3 trillion, citing disruptions from Iran tensions, with shares falling 2.2%; this affects global auto supply chains and investors.

Mount Dukono on Halmahera island in Indonesia erupted on Friday, killing three hikers—two foreigners and one local—and leaving 10 missing from a group of 20. Rescue teams are responding. In the United States, Presidents Lula of Brazil and Trump held three-hour talks at the White House on Thursday, stabilizing bilateral ties strained by tariffs; trade between the countries is worth billions of dollars annually. Tesla's Shanghai Gigafactory delivered 74,478 vehicles in April, up 36% from April 2024, driven by subsidies, EV demand, and exports amid competition from Chinese rivals."}
